const __vite_glob_0_24 = '---\ntitle: "COVID-19: Primary Thromboprophylaxis for Hospitalized Patients "\nsource: Thrombosis Canada - Clinical Guides\nurl: "https://thrombosiscanada.ca/hcp/practice/clinical_guides?language=en-ca&guideID=126"\nversion: 9\ndate_updated: "2026-02-06"\n---\n\n# COVID-19: Primary Thromboprophylaxis for Hospitalized Patients \n\n**Objective:** To outline a practical approach for the use of thromboprophylaxis in critically ill and non-critically ill patients hospitalized with COVID-19. \n\n---\n\n# **COVID-19 : Primary Thromboprophylaxis for Hospitalized Patient**\n\n## **Objective:**\n\nTo outline a practical approach for the use of thromboprophylaxis in critically ill and non-critically ill patients hospitalized with COVID-19.\n\n## **Background:**\n\nCOVID-19 is associated with an increased risk of thrombosis. Observational studies early in the pandemic reported high rates of venous thromboembolism (VTE) in hospitalized patients with COVID-19, with pooled incidences approximating 10-30% despite routine thromboprophylaxis. These rates are substantially higher than those historically documented for medically ill hospitalized patients without COVID-19 (less than 2%).\n\nPatients hospitalized with COVID-19 commonly carry traditional provoking factors for venous thromboembolism (VTE), including immobility, obesity, and advanced age. Further, SARS-CoV-2 infection directly inflames the endothelium, resulting in endotheliopathy and in-situ thrombosis, which may explain the disproportionately higher rates of PE than DVT in this patient population. Viral infection also drives a robust systemic inflammatory response which stimulates procoagulant pathways. Thrombogenicity in COVID-19 correlates with disease severity, which is reflected by higher VTE rates in patients needing ICU-level care.In turn, diagnosis of VTE is a poor prognostic marker in hospitalized patients with COVID-19.\n\nIn the absence of contraindications, all patients hospitalized with COVID-19 warrant pharmacologic thromboprophylaxis during their hospitalization. Multiple randomized control trials (RCTs) have evaluated the safety and efficacy of primary thromboprophylaxis at higher than standard dosing in selected critically ill and non-critically ill hospitalized patients with COVID-19 at low risk of bleeding. The purpose of this document is to provide recommendations for dosing and duration of pharmacologic thromboprophylaxis in patients hospitalized with COVID-19, on the basis of the results from these trials.\n\n## **Thromboprophylaxis for non-critically ill patients:**\n\n**Summary of the evidence:**Three RCTs compared therapeutic-dose to low- or intermediate-dose low molecular weight heparin (LMWH) and unfractionated heparin (UFH) in hospitalized non-critically ill patients with COVID-19 requiring low flow supplemental oxygen. Patients with high bleed risk were excluded. Therapeutic-dose LMWH/UFH improved clinical outcomes, prevented progression to critical illness, reduced rates of major thromboembolism, and trended to reduce all-cause mortality according to a meta-analysis of the three trials. This benefit seems to be specific to LMWH/UFH and is not seen with DOACs. When compared to standard thromboprophylaxis, Rivaroxaban 20 mg daily for 30 days did not improve clinical outcomes and increased risk of bleeding in one RCT. Details of each trial are summarized in **Table 1**.\n\n**Anticoagulant dose and timing:** Non-critically ill patients hospitalized for COVID-19 at low risk for bleeding should receive primary thromboprophylaxis at therapeutic dosing rather than standard or intermediate dosing. Therapeutic-dose thromboprophylaxis should be initiated upon admission, and continued throughout hospitalization for up to 14 days, in the absence of bleeding complications. Suggested regimens and dosing schedules are listed in **Table 5**. Patients with risk factors for bleeding should remain on standard-dose thromboprophylaxis throughout admission (see **Table 3** for variables associated with increased bleeding risk).\n\n**Anticoagulant choice:** LMWH or UFH should be used for thromboprophylaxis. We prefer LMWH over UFH as the former carries a lower risk of bleeding, heparin-induced thrombocytopenia, and minimizes personnel exposure. Any LMWH formulation listed in **Table 5** is appropriate to use. Direct oral anticoagulants (DOACs) have had mixed results and should not be used for thromboprophylaxis in this setting.\n\n## **Thromboprophylaxis for critically ill patients:**\n\nFor the purposes of this document, COVID-19-related critical illness is defined as the need for cardio-pulmonary organ support, such as oxygen by high-flow nasal canula, mechanical or non-invasive positive pressure ventilation, vasopressors, inotropes, or extra-corporeal membrane oxygenation (ECMO).\n\n**Summary of the evidence:** In critically ill patients with COVID-19, two RCTs compared therapeutic to standard-dose thromboprophylaxis with LMWH/UFH, and two RCTs compared intermediate to standard-dose thromboprophylaxis. Compared to controls, neither therapeutic nor intermediate dose LMWH/UFH improved clinical outcomes or mortality. Further, patients who received therapeutic dose anticoagulation trended to have higher rates of bleeding. Details of each trial are summarized in **Table 2**.\n\n**Anticoagulant regimen:** In patients with critical illness, thromboprophylaxis should be administered in the form of LMWH or UFH at standard dosing (see **Table 5**). UFH should be reserved for patients with contraindications to LMWH such as renal failure. Thromboprophylaxis should be initiated upon admission and continued throughout the duration of hospitalization.\n\n## **Post-discharge thromboprophylaxis:**\n\nExtended post-discharge thromboprophylaxis for up to 35 days with low-dose rivaroxaban 10 mg daily may be considered in select patients with high VTE risk (see **Table 4**), no risk factors for bleeding (see **Table 3**), and not receiving antithrombotic therapy for other indications. This recommendation is based on one RCT (n=320) in which rivaroxaban 10 mg daily for 35 days reduced rates of VTE without increasing bleeding in patients hospitalized for COVID-19. Notably, only patients who had a high thrombotic risk and a low risk of bleeding were selected for this study.\n\n## **Table 1. RCTs of thromboprophylaxis in non-critically ill patients with COVID-19**\n\n![](/clinical_guides/en-ca/images/COVID-Thromboprophylax Inpatients/Guide 55_Table 1_15Nov2024.png)\n\n*CRNMB= clinically relevant non-major bleed*\\*In the main cohort of both critically-ill and non-critically ill groups, rates of venous and arterial thromboembolism were reduced in the treatment arm compared to controls (10.9% vs. 29.0%, p<0.001) \n\\*\\*Defined as any VTE, myocardial infarction, stroke, systemic embolism, and major adverse limb event.\n\n## **Table 2. RCTs of thromboprophylaxis in critically ill patients with COVID-19**\n\n![](/wp-uploads/uploads/2023/02/Guide55_Figure2_23Feb2023-1024x575.png)\n\n\\*In the main cohort of both critically-ill and non-critically ill groups, rates of venous and arterial thromboembolism were reduced in the treatment arm compared to controls (10.9% vs. 29.0%, p<0.001)\n\n## **Table 3. Risk factors for bleeding**\n\n![](/clinical_guides/en-ca/images/COVID-Thromboprophylax Inpatients/Guide55_Figure 3_23Feb2023.png)\n\n## **Table 4. Risk factors for VTE in hospitalized patients**\n\n![](/clinical_guides/en-ca/images/COVID-Thromboprophylax Inpatients/Guide55_Figure 4_23Feb2023.png)\n\n## **Table 5. Options for thromboprophylaxis in patients hospitalized with COVID-19.**\n\n![](/wp-uploads/uploads/2023/02/Guide55_Figure-5_23Feb2023-1024x457.png)\n\n\\*For therapeutic dosing at extremes of weight, consider consulting a thrombosis expert. \n\\*\\*For standard thromboprophylaxis dosing at extremes of weight (<40kg or >100kg), refer to the Thrombosis Canada Guidelines “Thromboprophylaxis: Hospitalized Medical Patients”. \n¶Creatinine clearance, calculated by Cockcroft-Gault formula. \n¶¶Limit use of UFH to patients with contraindications to LMWH (allergy or CrCl <20ml/min).\n\n## **Special considerations:**\n\n**Patients who deteriorate during their hospitalization:**There is limited evidence to guide thromboprophylaxis management of hospitalized patients who eventually develop critical illness during their admission. Nonetheless, bleeding risk is substantially increased in critically ill patients with COVID-19 receiving therapeutic-dose anticoagulation. As such, hospitalized patients receiving therapeutic-dose anticoagulation should be stepped down to standard-dose anticoagulation if they deteriorate to require organ support, as already defined.\n\n**Management of thromboprophylaxis in patients with renal failure:** LMWH agents can bioaccumulate in patients with renal impairment. Therapeutic-dose enoxaparin and dalteparin should be avoided in patients with creatinine clearance (CrCl) less than 30 ml/min, as calculated by the Cockcroft-Gault equation. Therapeutic-dose tinzaparin may be considered until CrCl of 20ml/min.\n\nFor patients admitted with COVID-19 and CrCl less than 20 ml/min, including those requiring dialysis, unfractionated heparin (UFH) or dalteparin (at standard prophylactic dose) could be considered for thromboprophylaxis. Non-critically ill patients selected to receive therapeutic-dose thromboprophylaxis should receive IV UFH to target a therapeutic aPTT or anti-Xa level per institutional protocol. Critically ill patients with severe renal dysfunction could receive standard prophylactic dose subcutaneous UFH (5000U SQ BID or TID) or dalteparin 5000U SQ daily.\n\n**Patients receiving antithrombotic therapies for other indications at the time of admission**\n\n*a) Patients receiving antiplatelet therapy:*Hospitalized patients taking dual antiplatelet therapy (DAPT) should receive standard-dose rather than therapeutic-dose thromboprophylaxis in hospital, as bleed risk is increased. For select patients on single antiplatelet therapy in whom thrombotic risk significantly outweighs bleed risk, addition of therapeutic-dose thromboprophylaxis can be considered on a case-by-case basis. Consultation with a thrombosis or hematology expert may be appropriate in this setting.\n\n*b) Patients receiving therapeutic-dose anticoagulation:*Patients already on therapeutic-dose anticoagulation for other indications at the time of admission should remain on therapeutic-dose anticoagulation in hospital, if appropriate, irrespective of the severity of illness. Patients receiving DOACs or VKAs prehospitalization may be transitioned to LMWH while acutely ill. Oral anticoagulation can be resumed when the patient is nearing discharge and able to tolerate oral intake.\n\n**Use of biomarkers such as D-dimer to guide thromboprophylaxis:** There is no evidence to support the use of clinical biomarkers to guide thromboprophylaxis dosing or duration in patients with COVID-19. Although an elevated D-dimer may be associated with increased thrombotic risk, the benefit of therapeutic-dose thromboprophylaxis in this patient population is observed irrespective of the baseline D-dimer level. As such, neither the D-dimer nor other biomarkers should be incorporated into thromboprophylaxis decisions.\n\n## **Limitations to this guide:**\n\nThe phenotype of SARS-CoV2 illness is rapidly evolving. The studies used to formulate the above recommendations recruited patients during early stages of the pandemic, prior to the advent of universal vaccination and the emergence of novel strains. Further, these studies selected for a patient subpopulation at low risk of bleeding. As such, patient care should be individualized, and thromboprophylaxis decisions should be approached on a case-by-case basis. When possible, the patient’s preferences should be incorporated into treatment decisions, and shared decision-making should be carried out between members of the care team.\n\n### **Help sustain trusted thrombosis guidance**\n\nOngoing expert review and regular updates ensure Thrombosis Canada’s clinical guides remain current and reliable. Your support helps protect the quality and continuity of these resources for clinicians nationwide. [https://thrombosiscanada.ca/hcp/Donate-2](/hcp/Donate-2)\n\n**![](/clinical_guides/en-ca/images/Donate.png)**\n\n## **References:**\n\nAngelini DE, et al. COVID-19 and venous thromboembolism: A narrative review. Res Pract Thromb Haemost. 2022;6(2):e12666.\n\nFernández-Capitán C, et al. Presenting Characteristics, Treatment Patterns, and Outcomes among Patients with Venous Thromboembolism during Hospitalization for COVID-19. Semin Thromb Hemost. 2021;47(4):351–61.\n\nINSPIRATION Investigators. Effect of Intermediate-Dose vs Standard-Dose Prophylactic Anticoagulation on Thrombotic Events, Extracorporeal Membrane Oxygenation Treatment, or Mortality Among Patients With COVID-19 Admitted to the Intensive Care Unit: The INSPIRATION Randomized Clinical Trial. JAMA. 2021;325(16):1620–30.\n\nJiménez D, et al. Incidence of VTE and Bleeding Among Hospitalized Patients With Coronavirus Disease 2019: A Systematic Review and Meta-analysis. Chest:2021;159(3):1182–96.\n\nLopes RD, et al. Therapeutic versus prophylactic anticoagulation for patients admitted to hospital with COVID-19 and elevated D-dimer concentration (ACTION): an open-label, multicentre, randomised, controlled trial. The Lancet. 2021;397(10291):2253–63.\n\nMahan CE, et al. Thromboprophylaxis patterns, risk factors, and outcomes of care in the medically ill patient population. Thromb Res. 2013;132(5):520–6.\n\nMalas MB, et al. Thromboembolism risk of COVID-19 is high and associated with a higher risk of mortality: A systematic review and meta-analysis. EClinicalMedicine. 2020;29–30:100639.\n\nNopp S, et al. Risk of venous thromboembolism in patients with COVID‐19: A systematic review and meta‐analysis. Res Pract Thromb Haemost. 2020;4(7):1178–91.\n\nPerepu US, et al. Standard prophylactic versus intermediate dose enoxaparin in adults with severe COVID-19: A multi-center, open-label, randomized controlled trial. J Thromb Haemost. 2021;19(9):2225–34.\n\nRamacciotti E, et al. Rivaroxaban versus no anticoagulation for post-discharge thromboprophylaxis after hospitalisation for COVID-19 (MICHELLE): an open-label, multicentre, randomised, controlled trial. The Lancet. 2022;399(10319):50–9.\n\nSholzberg M, et al. Effectiveness of therapeutic heparin versus prophylactic heparin on death, mechanical ventilation, or intensive care unit admission in moderately ill patients with covid-19 admitted to hospital: RAPID randomised clinical trial. BMJ. 202; Oct 14:n2400.\n\nSholzberg M, et al. Randomized trials of therapeutic heparin for COVID-19: A meta-analysis. Res Pract Thromb Haemost. 2021;5(8):e12638.\n\nSpyropoulos AC, et al. Predictive and Associative Models to Identify Hospitalized Medical Patients at Risk for VTE. Chest. 2011;140(3):706–14.\n\nSpyropoulos AC, et al. Efficacy and Safety of Therapeutic-Dose Heparin vs Standard Prophylactic or Intermediate-Dose Heparins for Thromboprophylaxis in High-risk Hospitalized Patients With COVID-19: The HEP-COVID Randomized Clinical Trial. JAMA Intern Med. 2021;181(12):1612–20.\n\nStone GW, et al. Randomized Trial of Anticoagulation Strategies for Noncritically Ill Patients Hospitalized With COVID-19. J Am Coll Cardiol. 2023 May 9;81(18):1747-1762. doi: 10.1016/j.jacc.2023.02.041.\n\nThe ATTACC, ACTIV-4a, and REMAP-CAP Investigators. Therapeutic Anticoagulation with Heparin in Noncritically Ill Patients with Covid-19. N Engl J Med. 2021;385(9):790–802.\n\nTherapeutic Anticoagulation with Heparin in Critically Ill Patients with Covid-19. N Engl J Med. 2021;385(9):777–89.\n\n**Date of Version:**15November2024\n\n*Please note that the information contained herein is not to be interpreted as an alternative to medical advice from your doctor or other professional healthcare provider. If you have any specific questions about any medical matter, you should consult your doctor or other professional healthcare providers, and as such you should never delay seeking medical advice, disregard medical advice or discontinue medical treatment because of the information contained herein.*\n\n---\n\n*Source: [Thrombosis Canada Clinical Guides](https://thrombosiscanada.ca/hcp/practice/clinical_guides) | Last updated: 2026-02-06*\n';
